						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Productive-farms-can-be-greener-than-organic-study" title="Productive farms can be 'greener than organic': study" alt="link">Productive farms can be 'greener than organic': study</a></h2>

	
					<p>A study, led by Oxford University scientists, compared the environmental impact of different farming systems. Results of the study show farms that aim for high food production using environmentally-friendly practices could be better for the environment than both organic and conventional farms. The researchers found that ‘integrated’ farms that maximised crop yields whilst using environmentally-friendly techniques – such as crop rotation, organic fertilisers, over winter cover crops, and minimal use of pesticides – would use less energy and generate lower greenhouse gas emissions per unit of production than both organic and conventional farms. (<a href="http://www.physorg.com/news/2012-02-productive-farms-greener.html" target="_blank">Physorg</a>, 15/02/2012)</p>
							<p><span class="date">10/04/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Productive-farms-can-be-greener-than-organic-study">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Diverse-catches-better-for-fishery-ecosystem" title="Diverse catches better for fishery ecosystem" alt="link">Diverse catches better for fishery ecosystem</a></h2>

	
					<p>A research project fostered by the International Union for the Conservation of Nature's (IUCN ) Commission on Ecosystem Management which involved both conservation and fisheries scientists, aimed at understanding the impsact of fisheries on marine ecosystems. The related paper titled 'Reconsidering the Consequences of Selective Fisheries' concludes that a moderate level of fishing – spread across a wide range of species, stocks and sizes – can achieve high catch levels while conserving biodiversity. In contrast, increasing fishing selectivity to catch a small group of species and sizes neither maximises production nor minimises the ecological effects of fishing. The authors show that heavy selective fishing has caused structural changes to fish communities in the North Sea and elsewhere. By contrast, in several African small-scale inland fisheries, the fish size spectrum – a measure of ecological community structure – has been maintained under intensive and diverse fishing activities that cause high mortality with low selectivity (i.e. diverse catches). Implementing balanced harvesting requires coordinated management at an ecosystem level across all fisheries in a region. Ecosystem modelling could help in determining appropriate patterns of fishing. Markets and the processing sector in some regions would need encouragement to accommodate sizes and species not traditionally utilised.Visit website for more details: <a href="http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2012/03/120315095801.htm" target="_self">http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2012/03/120315095801.htm</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">10/04/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Diverse-catches-better-for-fishery-ecosystem">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-EU-project-to-look-at-the-international-spread-of-germs-on-food" title="New EU project to look at the international spread of germs on food" alt="link">New EU project to look at the international spread of germs on food</a></h2>

	
					<p>The project is entitled PROMISE (‘PROtection of consumers by MIcrobial risk mitigation through SEgregation of expertise’) and will be undertaken by twenty partners from various European countries. The project team comprises representatives of twelve academic institutions and six national authorities for food safety and is headed by the Institute of Milk Hygiene at the University of Veterinary Medicine, Vienna, Austria. The PROMISE project has the following goals: 1) make a survey of germs brought in together with food and investigate the potential of bacteria for causing disease; 2) pool data from throughout Europe to enable an accurate assessment of the risks posed by contaminated food of animal origin; 3) build up an extensive database of bacterial isolates identified in the course of the work. The results could help developing countries align their own food safety regulations with standards developed in export markets. (<a href="http://www.alphagalileo.org/ViewItem.aspx?ItemId=118437&amp;CultureCode=en" target="_blank">AlphaGalileo</a>, 16/03/2012)</p>
							<p><span class="date">10/04/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-EU-project-to-look-at-the-international-spread-of-germs-on-food">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-tools-help-countries-harness-the-potential-of-bioenergy-avoid-pitfalls" title="New tools help countries harness the potential of bioenergy, avoid pitfalls" alt="link">New tools help countries harness the potential of bioenergy, avoid pitfalls</a></h2>

	
					<p>The FAO has released a suite of guidance documents and policymaking tools that governments can use to help rural communities benefit from bioenergy development and ensure that biofuel crop production does not come at the expense of food security. Materials released by FAO's <a href="http://www.fao.org/bioenergy/foodsecurity/befsci/en/" target="_self">Bioenergy and Food Security Criteria and Indicators</a> (BEFSCI) Project include: methodologies for assessing the environmental and socioeconomic impacts of bioenergy production, indicators that can be measured when doing so, recommended good practices, and policy measures for promoting sustainable bionenergy development. (<a href="http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/123156/icode/" target="_blank">FAO</a>, 5/03/2012)</p>
							<p><span class="date">10/04/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-tools-help-countries-harness-the-potential-of-bioenergy-avoid-pitfalls">Read more...</a>
</div>
